# S01-T08: Adaptive Performance Manager + FPS Monitor

## Objective
Implement a performance monitoring system that adapts rendering quality based on device capabilities. When FPS drops, UI degrades gracefully per UI_REGULATION.ti.

## Design Regulation Compliance
From UI_REGULATION.ti §10:
> If FPS drops: reduce effects → disable glow → throttle graphs → simplify radar.
> Show: `PERFORMANCE MODE ACTIVE`

## Acceptance Criteria
- `src/services/PerformanceManager.ts`:
  - Tracks real-time FPS via rAF timing delta
  - Quality tiers: HIGH (>45fps), MEDIUM (25-45fps), LOW (<25fps)
  - Degradation cascade:
    1. HIGH → full rendering, all effects
    2. MEDIUM → disable glow effects, reduce graph update rate
    3. LOW → throttle graphs to 10fps, simplify radar (no sweep), disable particle effects, **globally disable Framer Motion animations** via `MotionConfig`
  - Memory pressure detection via `performance.memory` (when available)
  - Emits `PERFORMANCE_MODE_ACTIVE` event when tier drops below HIGH
- `src/shared/hooks/usePerformance.ts`:
  - Returns `{ fps, tier, isPerformanceMode, memoryUsage }`
  - Components subscribe to `tier` and conditionally reduce visual complexity
- `src/shared/ui/PerformanceBanner.tsx`:
  - Shows `PERFORMANCE MODE ACTIVE` banner (amber text, 120ms fade-in)
  - Auto-hides when tier returns to HIGH (after 3s stability)
- Integrates with RenderScheduler to adjust priority thresholds

## Steps
1. Create PerformanceManager singleton
2. Implement FPS tracking + quality tier logic
3. Implement degradation cascade
4. Create usePerformance hook
5. Create PerformanceBanner component
6. Wire into RenderScheduler for adaptive throttling
